FIRST AMENDED AND RESATED MASTER INTERCONNECTION SERVICES AGREEMENT This First Amended and Restated Master Interconnection Services Agreement (this “MISA”), dated as of August 10, 2020 (the “Effective Date”) , is entered into by and among Big Sky North, LLC (“Interconnection Provider”), and each Person that becomes a party hereto by execution and delivery of a Service Agreement in the form of Exhibit A (such Persons, the “Users”). With respect to each User, this MISA, any exhibits, schedules and appendices hereto, together with such User’s Service Agreement, shall be referred to as the “Agreement” between such User and the other parties hereto.
RECITALS
A. Each User owns and operates a Project (as defined below).
B. Interconnection Provider owns, or has certain rights to use, the Interconnection Facilities (as defined below), and each User desires to utilize such Interconnection Facilities in order to deliver electricity from its Project to the Point of Interconnection (as defined below).
C. Interconnection Provider and each User desire to set forth their respective rights and obligations with respect to the Projects and the Interconnection Facilities.
D. Interconnection Provider and each User have entered into that certain Master Interconnection Services Agreement, dated as of August 1, 2018 (the “Original Agreement”).
E. The parties to the Original Agreement wish to amend and restate the Original Agreement as of the Effective Date on the terms and conditions set forth herein in order to reflect the inclusion of the Users’ energy storage facilities.
NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the foregoing recitals, the mutual promises contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and adequacy of which are hereby acknowledged by the Parties, the Parties agree as follows:
1. DEFINITIONS AND INTERPRETATION
1.1 Definitions. Unless otherwise noted, capitalized terms not defined in the body of this Agreement have the following meanings.
“Affiliate” means, with respect to any Party, any Person directly or indirectly controlling, controlled by or under common control with such Party. The term “control” and correlative terms includes the possession, directly or indirectly and whether acting alone or in conjunction with others, of the authority to direct or cause the direction of the management or policies of a Person, whether through the ownership of voting securities, by contract, or otherwise.
“Agreement” has the meaning set forth in the Preamble.
“Big Sky Facilities” means the Shared Assets (as defined in the Big Sky Shared Facilities Agreement), as further described on Exhibit E.
“Big Sky North Busbar Extension” means the extension of the Big Sky Substation 220 kV busbar, extending south of the Big Sky Substation near the corner of Avenue J and 100th Street West, Lancaster, California.
“Big Sky North Facilities” means the Big Sky North Substation and the 220 kV interconnection facilities and associated equipment extending from the Big Sky North Substation to the Big Sky Substation, as well as the Big Sky North Busbar Extension and associated equipment, as further described on Exhibit E.
“Big Sky North Substation” means the substation to be constructed by Interconnection Provider located at 9507 West Avenue G-8, Lancaster, California 93534 that connects to the Big Sky Substation through a 220 kV generation tie line.
“Big Sky Shared Facilities Agreement” means the Third Amended and Restated Big Sky Shared Facilities Agreement, dated as of August 1, 2018, by and among Interconnection Provider, sPower Services, LLC and the other parties thereto, which governs the shared use of the Big Sky Facilities, as it may be amended, assigned, or supplemented from time to time. “Big Sky Substation” means the substation on the corner of Avenue J and 100th Street West, Lancaster, California that was constructed by Affiliates of Interconnection Provider pursuant to the Big Sky Shared Facilities Agreement.
“CAISO” means the California Independent System Operator.
“Capacity Log” means a log, in the form attached hereto as Exhibit F, showing the Reserved Capacity and Cost Percentage of each User.
“Casualty Event” means an event that causes all or a portion of the Big Sky North Facilities to be damaged, destroyed or rendered unfit for normal use for any reason whatsoever.
“Condemnation Event” means any compulsory transfer or taking or transfer under threat of compulsory transfer or taking of all or a material part of the Big Sky North Facilities by any Governmental Authority or entity acting under power of eminent domain.
“Conditional Use Permit” or “CUP” means, (1) with respect to the Big Sky North Substation and 220 kV generation tie line to the Big Sky Substation, that certain Conditional Use Permit No. 14-15e issued to Sustainable Power Group, LLC by the City of Lancaster on September 22, 2015, as amended from time to time, (2) with respect to the Big Sky North Busbar Extension, that certain Conditional Use Permit No. 17-04 issued to sPower Development Company, LLC by the City of Lancaster on December 20, 2017, as amended from time to time, and (3) with respect to the Big Sky North Facilities located in the Big Sky Substation, Conditional Use Permit No 13-06 issued to Silverado Power, LLC dba Plainview Solarworks, LLC by the City of Lancaster on July 17, 2013, as amended from time to time.
“Confidential Information,” with respect to a given Disclosing Party and the respective Receiving Party, means, collectively and individually, all data, materials and information (including software, data, technology, know-how, trade secrets, processes, ideas, inventions (whether patentable or not), prototypes, schematics, design plans, drawings, pricing information, customer and service provider lists, business arrangements, business information, financial information, financial results, technical information, analyses, forecasts, compilations, studies, contracts, agreements, and planning or strategy information) provided by or on behalf of a Party (each Party in such capacity, a “Disclosing Party”) to the other Party (each Party in such capacity, a “Receiving Party”) or the Receiving Party’s Representatives, or to which the Receiving Party or the Receiving Party’s Representatives are given access by or on behalf of the Disclosing Party, whether verbally or in written or electronic form, related to the Disclosing Party, any Project, the Interconnection Facilities, the Interconnection Premises or the Users in connection with this Agreement. Notwithstanding the foregoing, Confidential Information under this Agreement does not include any information that: (A) the Receiving Party can demonstrate is now publicly available, or that later becomes publicly available through no action by the Receiving Party or the Receiving Party’s Representatives in violation of this Agreement; (B) the Receiving Party can demonstrate is already in the possession of the Receiving Party or the Receiving Party’s Representatives and is not subject to a confidentiality or fiduciary obligation at the time of the information’s disclosure under this Agreement; (C) the Receiving Party can demonstrate is lawfully received from any source other than the Disclosing Party or the Disclosing Party’s Representatives under circumstances not involving, to the Receiving Party’s knowledge, a breach of any fiduciary or confidentiality obligation; or (D) the Receiving Party can demonstrate is independently developed by or for the Receiving Party or the Receiving Party’s Representatives without reference to, or the use of, any portion of the Confidential Information.
“Consent of the Users” means the written consent of (a) Users that hold fifty-one percent (51%) or more of the aggregate Reserved Capacity of all Users whose Projects are connected and Energized, and (b) each User that has a Reserved Capacity equal to or greater than 100 MW. With respect to decisions affecting a Managed Asset, only Users with an ownership interest in such asset shall be considered in determining whether the Consent of the Users has occurred. “Co-Owner” has the meaning provided in the Big Sky Shared Facilities Agreement. “Cost Percentage” is a fraction, with respect to a User, where (a) the numerator is the Nameplate Capacity of such User’s Project or Projects with respect to each segment of the Big Sky North Facilities or the Managed Assets and (b) the denominator is the Nameplate Capacity of all of the current Users’ Projects utilizing each segment of the Big Sky North Facilities or the Managed Assets. Any Person becoming a New User under this Agreement will be assigned a Cost Percentage with respect to each segment of the Big Sky North Facilities and the Managed Assets based on an adjusted aggregated capacity that utilizes each segment of the Big Sky North Facilities or the Managed Assets that includes the New User’s Project Nameplate Capacity. Upon the admittance of a New User, the Cost Percentage of all of the existing Users will be similarly adjusted by the new denominator (if applicable) representing the new aggregated Nameplate Capacity of all Users’ Projects. The Cost Percentage shall be determined and applied with respect to those segments of the Interconnection Facilities and Managed Assets as specified in Exhibit C to this Agreement, as such exhibit may be updated by notice to the Users from time to time.
“Default Rate” means a rate per annum equal to the lesser of (a) a varying rate per annum equal to the sum of (i) the three (3) month LIBOR as published in The Wall Street Journal, with adjustments in that varying rate to be made on the same date as any change in that rate is so published, plus (ii) two percent (2%) per annum, and (b) the maximum rate permitted by Law. If LIBOR is no longer available, then the Default Rate shall utilize a successor rate or reasonable replacement rate, as selected by Interconnection Provider.
“Disclosing Party” has the meaning set forth in the definition of “Confidential Information.”
“Effective Date” has the meaning set forth in the preamble to this MISA.
“Eligible Customer” means any Person (i) owning and operating an energy storage facility or generating electric energy for sale or resale and (ii) that is an Affiliate of Interconnection Provider. A Person is not an Eligible Customer if it serves load.
“Emergency” shall mean any occurrence, in the reasonable judgment of Interconnection Provider or a User, that may arise that requires immediate action and which constitutes a serious actual or potential hazard to the safety of Persons or property, that may materially interfere with the safe, economical or environmentally sound operation of the Big Sky North Facilities or any Project, or that would violate any applicable Law, Governmental Approvals, Interconnection Premises Agreements, or the CUP. “Energized” shall refer to a state of completion where electrical current begins to flow. “Environmental Laws” means all Laws relating to the protection of the environment, health or safety or the use, generation, release, treatment, storage, disposal or exposure to Hazardous Materials, including the Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation and Liability Act of 1980, as amended by the Superfund Amendments and Reauthorization Act of 1986; the Clean Water Act; the Resource, Conservation and Recovery Act of 1976; the Occupational Safety and Health Act of 1970; and the Clean Air Act, all as amended, and equivalent State of California laws and regulations.
“Event of Default” has the meaning set forth in Section 14.1.
“EWG” means an “exempt wholesale generator,” as such term is defined in Section 1262(6) of the Public Utility Holding Company Act of 2005 and the FERC’s rules at 18 C.F.R. § 366.1.
“FERC” means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
“Financing Party” means, with respect to each User, the agent or lead bank and any other financial institutions that are party or a potential or prospective party to a loan agreement, hedge agreement, tax equity financing documents (including through a partnership flip arrangement or other similar financing) or other debt, equity or other type of financing or investment instrument with such User, including a sale-leaseback.
“Force Majeure” means acts of God or any other casualty or occurrence, condition, event or circumstance of any kind or nature not reasonably within the affected Party’s control and which could not have been avoided by reasonable measures or foreseeable by the affected, including national or regional strikes, slow-downs or labor difficulties (other than any such action by or in relation to the Interconnection Provider or any of its subcontractors), fires, floods, earthquakes, explosions, natural disasters or other hazards, acts of public enemies, riots, civil commotions, insurrection, or war. Force Majeure expressly does not include any delay in performing or failure of performance of any contractual provision by a Party (except to the extent caused by a Force Majeure event); late delivery or breakage of equipment or materials (except to the extent caused by a Force Majeure event); or economic hardship.
“Governmental Approval” means any: (a) permit, license, certificate, concession, approval, consent, ratification, permission, clearance, confirmation, exemption, waiver, franchise, certification, designation, rating, registration, variance, qualification, accreditation or authorization issued, granted, given or otherwise made available by or under the authority of any Governmental Authority or pursuant to any Law, and any grading, building, or conditional use permits affecting the applicable real property and in effect with respect to the Projects, the Interconnection Facilities, or any part of them, as applicable to the Big Sky North Facilities, or (b) right under any contract with any Governmental Authority.
“Governmental Authority” means any court, tribunal, authority, agency, commission, official or other instrumentality, including regulatory authorities and bodies, of the United States or any state, county, city or other political subdivision; any quasi-governmental regulatory authority, such as NERC or CAISO, acting under delegated authority; any arbitrator; or any judicial or quasi-judicial tribunal of competent jurisdiction.
“Hazardous Materials” means any hazardous or toxic substance or waste, pollutant or contaminant as defined under applicable Environmental Laws, including petroleum products, asbestos, polychlorinated biphenyls and radioactive materials.
“Interconnection Agreement” means either the (i) Large Generator Interconnection Agreement by and among Antelope Expansion 2, LLC, Southern California Edison Company (“SCE”), and the California Independent System Operator Corporation (the “CAISO”), dated as of August 7, 2017, or (ii) the Amended and Restated Large Generator Interconnection Agreement by and among the Co-Owners of the Big Sky Shared Facilities Agreement, Southern California Edison Company (“SCE”), and the California Independent System Operator Corporation (the “CAISO”), dated as of April 13, 2016, together in either case with all agreements, schedules, appendices, exhibits and other documents ancillary thereto, as such agreements may be amended, assigned, or supplemented from time to time.
“Interconnection Expenses” has the meaning set forth in Section 4.2.
“Interconnection Facilities” means, collectively, the Big Sky North Facilities and the Big Sky Facilities. Interconnection Facilities do not include Managed Assets. “Interconnection Facilities Representative” has the meaning set forth in Section 5.2. “Interconnection Premises” means that real property underlying the Big Sky North Facilities.
“Interconnection Premises Agreements” means those agreements that provide Interconnection Provider with the rights and authority to construct, own, and operate the Big Sky North Facilities on the Interconnection Premises. “Interconnection Provider” means Big Sky North, LLC or its successor hereunder. “Laws” means any applicable constitutional provisions, statutes, acts, codes, laws, rules, regulations, ordinances, orders, decrees, rulings, judgments or decisions of a Governmental Authority or arbitral body. “Liabilities” means any and all claims, actions, debts, losses, liabilities, damages, expenses, awards, judgments, settlement payments, fines, penalties, costs, royalties, assessments (tax or otherwise), proceedings, deficiencies or obligations, whether civil or criminal, including those arising out of any investigation, action, claim, settlement, compromise, judgment or award, by any private party or Governmental Authority, of any nature, whether known or unknown, absolute, accrued, contingent or otherwise, and whether due or to become due, and whether or not resulting from third party claims, and any out-of-pocket costs and expenses (including court costs and fees, and reasonable legal counsels’, accountants’, or other fees and expenses) incurred in defending against or investigating any of the same.
“Liens” means all mortgages, deeds of trust, liens, debentures, security interests, pledges, conditional sale contracts, proceedings, judgment liens, orders, rights of first refusal, charges and other encumbrances or restrictions of any kind, whether recorded or unrecorded.
“Loss Event” means a Casualty Event or a Condemnation Event.
“Managed Assets” means those Project Specific Assets that are owned and shared by two or more Users, as specified in Exhibit C to this Agreement, and that are managed (but not owned) by Interconnection Provider for purposes of effectuating interconnection service for the Projects. For purposes of clarity, Managed Assets are not considered “Interconnection Facilities” under this Agreement.
“MISA” has the meaning set forth in the Preamble. “MW” means megawatt (alternating current). “Nameplate Capacity” means (i) with respect to a solar photovoltaic facility, the generating capacity of such Project as measured in alternating current at the Point of Interconnection (in MW), and (ii) with respect to a facility that includes energy storage, the maximum rate of energy discharge by such Project starting from the fully charged state of the energy storage, as measured in alternating current at the Point of Interconnection, as defined by physical and operational controls constraining the rate of such Project’s discharge of energy. By way of example only, if the maximum aggregate energy output of the inverters of a solar plus energy storage project is 55 MWac, but software and power plant controls limit its rate of discharge to an aggregate of 50 MWac at the Point of Interconnection, then the Nameplate Capacity of that energy storage project would be deemed to be 50 MWac.
“NERC” means the North American Electric Reliability Corporation.
“Net Revenue Loss” means the sum of (a) the product of (i) the MWh of electricity that would have been produced by the applicable Project (based on the CAISO eligible intermittent resource protocol forecast adjusted for Project availability, or if such forecast is unavailable or inaccurate, the best available weather, historical, availability or other pertinent data) during the applicable period, and (ii) the price such electricity would have been sold by the affected User under such User’s power purchase agreement had the electricity been produced, or if such User has no power purchase agreement, then at the Resource-Specific Settlement Interval LMP (as defined in the CAISO Tariff) for electricity during such period, (b) if the User is eligible to receive renewable energy credits, including those granted pursuant to law, regulation, certification, markets, trading, off-set, private transaction, renewable portfolio standards or voluntary programs (“RECs”), the dollar value for the RECs that would have been payable to the affected User based on the average price per MWh of RECs of two valid seller price quotes for lots of not less than 5,000 MWhs of comparable RECs from nationally recognized REC brokers; provided such User is not otherwise compensated for RECs as part of subsection (a) above, and (c) any penalties or liquidated damages assessed against such User for failing to produce electricity such User was contractually obligated to produce, grossed up on an after-tax basis and taking into account applicable state and local taxes, provided, however, if the Project is an energy storage facility, then Net Revenue Loss means those reasonably calculated and substantiated lost revenues occurring under such User’s power purchase agreement or that otherwise would have been paid to such User according to the CAISO Tariff for electrical energy, capacity, or ancillary services during such period.
“New User” has the meaning set forth in Section 6.12.
“Original Agreement” has the meaning set forth in Recital E above.
“Other Indemnified Parties” has the meaning set forth in Section 11.2.
“Parties” and “Party” means, individually and collectively, as the context requires, the Interconnection Provider or any User(s).
“Permitted Liens” means (a) liens imposed by law securing the charges, claims, demands or levies of mechanics, materialmen, carriers, warehousemen and other like Persons which (i) are incurred in connection with the interconnection of one or more Projects to the Big Sky North Facilities or the construction, operation or maintenance of the Interconnection Facilities or any Managed Assets, and (ii) secure obligations (A) that are not yet due or (B)(1) that are being contested in good faith and by appropriate proceedings diligently pursued, which proceedings have the effect of preventing the foreclosure, forfeiture or sale of the property or assets subject to such lien, (2) for which adequate reserves (in the good faith judgment of the Manager) have been established in accordance with GAAP or which are secured by bonds or other security reasonably satisfactory to the Manager, and (3) as to which the property or assets subject to such lien is not yet subject to foreclosure, sale or loss on account thereof, (b) pledges or deposits to secure the performance of bids, tenders, trade contracts and leases (other than for the repayment of borrowed money) incurred in the ordinary course of business; (c) pledges or deposits to secure regulatory or statutory obligations, surety and appeal bonds, performance bonds and other obligations of a like nature incurred in the ordinary course of business securing the payment of amounts not yet due and payable or amounts being contested in good faith and by appropriate proceedings; (d) all exceptions listed in the title policy with respect to the Interconnection Premises or other land use restrictions that do not impair the use or value of the Interconnection Facilities in any material respect, in each case whether now or hereafter in existence; (e) mortgages against the fee interest of the real property subject to an Interconnection Premises Agreement, provided that the mortgagee thereof shall have subordinated its interest to the interest of the Company or shall have agreed not to foreclose or otherwise disturb the possession by the Project Company of the real property interests in the absence of a default by the Company (beyond any applicable grace period), under the terms of the Shared Premises Agreement, in either case in a written agreement, in recordable form; (f) Liens and any right of setoff in favor of a bank or other financial institution arising by operation of applicable Laws or in the ordinary course of business encumbering deposits held by such bank or financial institution; (g) Liens for taxes (other than for taxes not yet due or as provided in Section 6.2) and (h) judgment Liens that do not involve any immediate risk of forfeiture of the Interconnection Facilities and, within ten (10) Business Days of their existence or after the entry thereof, are being contested in good faith and by appropriate proceedings, and adequate reserves with respect thereto are maintained on the books of the applicable Person in accordance with GAAP or the Lien is covered by insurance, bonds or other reasonable security.
“Person” means any individual, partnership, joint stock company, corporation, limited liability company, trust, unincorporated association or joint venture, Governmental Authority, or other entity. “Point of Interconnection” means the point of interconnection under the Interconnection Agreement pursuant to which a Project interconnects with the electric transmission facilities of SCE.
“Project(s)” means, in the case of each User, its solar photovoltaic or energy storage facility, in whole or in part, (inclusive of modules, inverters, and associated infrastructure) used to generate or store and discharge electric energy, capacity, or ancillary services or, in the case of the Interconnection Provider, all or any portion of the Big Sky North Facilities. “Project Site(s)” means the real property upon which each User’s Project is located. “Project Specific Assets” means, for each Project, any of the assets comprising such Project, whether sole-use or shared with other Projects, located at a point before the Big Sky North Facilities (including Managed Assets, the collector system for the Project and Project specific meters, switches, current transformers, potential transformers, step-up transformers, transformer bays reclosers, switches, VAR compensation, the Project Site underlying such Project, and the agreements and contractual arrangements related to such Project and Project Site (including the User’s interest in its respective Interconnection Agreement)). For the avoidance of doubt, the Project Specific Assets shall exclude all of the Interconnection Facilities and the Interconnection Premises.
“Prudent Industry Practices” means any of the practices, methods, and standards of care, skill, safety and diligence, as the same may change from time to time, but applied in light of the facts known at the time, as are generally applied or utilized under comparable circumstances by reasonably experienced and prudent professionals in respect of the design, development, construction, commissioning, maintenance, financing and operation of facilities located in California of comparable type and complexity to the applicable Projects. “Prudent Industry Practices” does not necessarily mean the best practice, method, or standard of care, skill, safety and diligence in all cases, but is instead intended to encompass a range of acceptable practices, methods, and standards.
“Receiving Party” has the meaning set forth in the definition of “Confidential Information.”
“Representatives” means, with respect to a Party, such Party’s Affiliates, officers, directors, members, shareholders, partners, employees, lenders, tax equity investors, contractors, vendors, suppliers, advisors, consultants, agents and representatives.
“Reserved Capacity” has the meaning provided in Section 2 hereunder. “Restoration Proposal” has the meaning set forth in Section 8.8. “SCE” means Southern California Edison Company. “Service Agreement” means that standard form agreement provided at Exhibit A of this Agreement that provides User- and Project-specific details and that, once fully executed, binds a User to the terms and conditions of this Agreement. “Service Commencement Date” means the first date on which a User purchases, and the Interconnection Provider provides, firm transmission services, as such date is specified in a User’s respective Service Agreement.
“Service Term” means the term of firm service, expressed in calendar years, specified in each User’s Service Agreement, as such term may be extended.
“Substation Premises” means that real property identified in Exhibit B of this Agreement.
“Substation Premises Agreements” mean each contract pursuant to which Interconnection Provider has been granted a lease, right of way, access right, fee interest or similar rights over the Substation Premises.
“Tax” means all federal, state, provincial, territorial, municipal, local or foreign income, profits, franchise, gross receipts, environmental (including taxes under Internal Revenue Code § 59A), customs, duties, net worth, sales, use, goods and services, withholding, value added, ad valorem, employment, social security, disability, occupation, pension, real property, personal property (tangible and intangible), stamp, transfer, conveyance, severance, production, excise and other taxes, withholdings, duties, levies, imposts and other similar charges and assessments (including any and all fines, penalties and additions attributable to or otherwise imposed on or with respect to any such taxes, charges, fees, levies or other assessments, and interest thereon) imposed by or on behalf of any Governmental Authority, in each case whether such Tax arises by law, contract or otherwise.
“User” has the meaning set forth in the Preamble.
“User Indemnified Parties” has the meaning set forth in Section 11.
2. SERVICE AGREEMENTS
Interconnection Provider may, subject to Section 6.12, offer a Service Agreement to each Eligible Customer who has requested transmission services across the Interconnection Facilities by submitting a written application for such services to Interconnection Provider. Interconnection Provider shall promptly notify each existing User of its receipt of any such application from an Eligible Customer. From the Service Commencement Date and during the Service Term specified in a User’s Service Agreement, such User shall purchase, and the Interconnection Provider shall provide, firm transmission service over the Interconnection Facilities pursuant to the terms and conditions of this Agreement. Each Service Agreement entitles its respective User to a reservation of, and firm service over, capacity on the Interconnection Facilities in an amount specified in such User’s Project (the “Reserved Capacity”). Interconnection Provider may update the form of Service Agreement as needed from time to time in order to address construction, operations, or maintenance issues. Interconnection Provider shall not permit the aggregate Reserved Capacity of all Users or the aggregate Nameplate Capacity of all Projects to exceed 650 MW.
3. INTERCONNECTION FACILITIES
3.1 Interconnection Facilities. The Interconnection Provider has caused or will cause the procurement, installation, and/or construction of, as applicable, the Big Sky North Facilities prior to the first User’s Service Commencement Date. In addition, as of the date of each User’s Service Commencement Date, the Interconnection Provider is a Co-Owner under the Big Sky Shared Facilities Agreement and, as such, has contractual rights to utilize its undivided interests in the Big Sky Facilities to transmit energy from each User’s Project across the Big Sky Facilities to the Point of Interconnection. As such, pursuant to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, the transmission services provided by Interconnection Provider under this Agreement shall entitle each User to firm transmission service over both the Big Sky North Facilities and the Big Sky Facilities which, together, comprise the Interconnection Facilities hereunder.
3.2 Substation Premises.
3.2.1 Interconnection Provider irrevocably and unconditionally grants to each User and its respective successors and assigns, for the benefit of and appurtenant to each User’s Project, respectively, sub-easement and sublease rights over, across and under the Substation Premises for the purpose of constructing, operating and maintaining Project Specific Assets, including, without limitation, overhead transmission lines and related facilities, and ingress and egress access thereto as and to the extent such rights are granted to Interconnection Provider pursuant to the Substation Premises Agreement. Each User shall comply with all the terms and conditions of the Interconnection Premises Agreements and the Governmental Approvals.
3.2.2 The Interconnection Provider shall timely execute the necessary instruments to ensure each User has sufficient rights to use the Substation Premises on which the Big Sky North Facilities substation is located.
3.2.3 Any amounts due under the terms of the Interconnection Premises Agreements and the CUP shall be paid by the Interconnection Provider, subject to reimbursement by the Users in accordance with Section 4.
3.3 Access to Interconnection Facilities. Each User and its Representatives shall have access to the Substation Premises for the installation, maintenance, or repairs of the Project Specific Assets, or the Big Sky North Substation, as applicable. The Interconnection Provider, a User and/or any User’s Representatives shall follow all applicable safety, security and site rules established by the agreement of the Users and Interconnection Provider, and shall comply with the CUP and all applicable Substation Premises Agreements, Laws and Governmental Approvals when on the Substation Premises or accessing the Big Sky North Facilities, except to the extent that following any such rule would violate applicable Law. In the event of an Emergency, prior notice is not required to access the Big Sky North Facilities substation to respond to the Emergency, but the User shall provide notice of access to Interconnection Provider and the other Users as soon as reasonably practicable thereafter (no more than twenty-four (24) hours after access).
3.4 No Interference, Cooperation and Over-Burdening. A User’s use of the Interconnection Facilities and the operation of its Project shall not interfere with the use and enjoyment by the other Users of their respective rights to use the Interconnection Facilities or the operation of its Project, except as specifically provided herein. Subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, each User hereby consents to the development and operation of each of the Projects owned by the other Users, and each User shall cooperate in good faith to accommodate the other User’s use of the Interconnection Facilities for the benefit of the Projects as contemplated by this Agreement. No User will use or permit the use of the Interconnection Facilities in any manner that would create waste or nuisance, or that would jeopardize the issuance or maintenance of any insurance policy relating to the Interconnection Facilities or any Governmental Approval as to the Interconnection Facilities or any Project, nor otherwise conduct or permit to be conducted operations on its Project Site which would have similar effects on, or otherwise damage or interfere with, the Interconnection Facilities. All incremental costs and expenses associated with a User interconnecting a Project into the Interconnection Facilities shall be for the account of, and paid for, by such User.
3.5 Additional Facilities. Except as otherwise provided in this Agreement, no User shall construct, install or place any additional facilities within the Interconnection Premises.
3.6 Conditions to Connecting Projects to the Interconnection Facilities. Any User connecting its Project to the Interconnection Facilities shall (a) not interfere with the use or access by the other Users of the Interconnection Facilities, except as may be necessary during the installation, repair, or replacement of Interconnection Facilities, (b) to the extent commercially reasonable, schedule during an off-peak and/or low solar insolation period any required disconnection of the Big Sky North Facilities to conduct construction activities to minimize the impact on the Projects of the other Users, (c) provide at least thirty (30) days’ prior written notice to each User of commencement of such construction activities together with a reasonably detailed description thereof, (d) provide at least thirty (30) days’ prior written notice to each User of any planned outages, and the durations thereof, of the Big Sky North Facilities that would result in a disconnection of another User’s Project, (e) take into consideration, to the extent commercially reasonable, any changes in the construction plans or timing of construction required by another User, (f) be responsible for obtaining and complying with any necessary Governmental Approvals and providing documentary evidence of such Governmental Approvals to the Users and Interconnection Provider, and (g) compensate each other User for its Net Revenue Loss as a result of lost generation or disrupted operation due to an outage or disconnection of such User’s Project. Any Users connecting its own Project to the Big Sky North Facilities, shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Users from all Liabilities, including third party claims, property and revenue losses incurred, related to such construction or installation activities, but such installing User may seek reimbursement for such indemnified costs from insurance required by Section 12 to the extent such insurance provides coverage for such indemnified costs.
4. INTERCONNECTION EXPENSES
4.1 Liabilities for the Account of the Users; No Charging of Fees, Premiums or Profits. Except as specifically set forth in this Agreement, each User shall be solely responsible for its Liabilities relating to its Project and Project Specific Assets, including without limitation, all Liabilities arising from acquiring, designing, installing, constructing, using, operating, maintaining and repairing its Project Specific Assets. Each User shall, at its sole cost and expense, maintain in good working order and repair at all times each part of its Project that connects with, will connect with, or affects the Interconnection Facilities or the Substation Premises. Each User shall be responsible for all Liabilities arising from such User’s actions or inactions in violation of this Agreement.
4.2 Interconnection Expenses.
4.2.1 The Users each shall be responsible for and shall reimburse the Interconnection Provider (in accordance with Section 4.3) for Liabilities arising under or relating to the following (collectively, the “Interconnection Expenses”), in proportion to its respective Cost Percentage for each portion of the Big Sky North Facilities:
(a) any fees, expenses or liabilities incurred by or otherwise allocable to Interconnection Provider for the use, maintenance, operation, repair, and inspection of the Big Sky North Facilities, once constructed;
(b) the Liabilities arising under any Interconnection Premises Agreements, and the use, maintenance, repair, and inspection of the Interconnection Premises;
(c) any fees, expenses or liabilities incurred by or otherwise allocable to Interconnection Provider hereunder (including Liabilities arising under the CUP and the use, maintenance, operation, repair, and inspection of the Interconnection Premises); and
(d) any fees, expenses or liabilities incurred by or otherwise allocable to Interconnection Provider under the Big Sky Shared Facilities Agreement; provided that, solely with respect to Liabilities arising under this Section 4.2.1(d), the Cost Percentage of the Users shall be adjusted to reflect, and give credit for, any payment by a User directly under the Big Sky Shared Facilities Agreement.
If an Interconnection Expense applies generally to the Big Sky North Facilities and not to any particular segment, such as the cost of insurance, each User shall pay, and Interconnection Provider will be reimbursed by each User for, the Interconnection Expense in accordance with the Cost Percentage of such Users that is interconnected to the Big Sky North Facilities.
4.2.2 Notwithstanding the foregoing, (i) the initial User of the Interconnection Facilities shall reimburse the Interconnection Provider for any fees, expenses and Liabilities incurred by or otherwise allocable to Interconnection Provider for the construction of the Big Sky North Facilities prior to the Service Commencement Date; and (ii) the cost and expense of any Project Specific Assets and the connection and integration of Project Specific Assets with any Interconnection Facilities (including without limitation, any design, procurement, construction, or installation costs) shall not be considered Interconnection Expenses hereunder. In addition, each User shall be individually responsible for any fees, expenses or liabilities incurred by or otherwise allocable to Interconnection Provider for the construction, use, maintenance, operation, repair, and inspection of any incremental equipment added to the Big Sky North Facilities, as applicable, for the purpose of accommodating the interconnection of such User’s Project.
4.3 Invoicing; Late Payments. No later than the first day of each calendar month, beginning with a User’s respective Service Commencement Date, the Interconnection Provider shall invoice such User for its respective portions of the Interconnection Expenses for the prior month. Interconnection Provider’s invoice shall include a detailed breakdown of the Interconnection Expenses and each User’s share of the Interconnection Expenses, along with wire transfer instructions for making payment to Interconnection Provider. The Users shall make all payments to Interconnection Provider (or directly to the other Users to whom the Interconnection Expenses may be payable) under this Section 4.3 by wire transfer of immediately available funds as provided in the Interconnection Provider’s invoice, within thirty (30) days of receipt of such invoice. All sums not paid within thirty (30) days after receipt of Interconnection Provider’s invoice shall thereafter bear interest at the Default Rate. Each User will have the right to audit, and receive supporting documentation for, any expenses or other amounts required to be paid by such User under this Agreement. If there is a dispute as to any amount invoiced by Interconnection Provider, the Users shall pay all amounts not in dispute in accordance with this Section 4.3. The Users shall pay any disputed amount ultimately determined as payable with interest thereon at the Default Rate accruing from the date of receipt of the Interconnection Provider’s disputed invoice.
5. USE OF INTERCONNECTION FACILITIES AND MANAGED ASSETS
5.1 Use by Projects. Subject to the other requirements of this Agreement, each User shall have the right to use that transmission capacity over the Interconnection Facilities on a firm basis to the extent of the Reserved Capacity set forth in such User’s Service Agreement. The Users shall share line losses according to pro rata capacity shares. The foregoing rights include use of any electrical transmission lines, transformers, substations, and other electrical components to collect and transmit electricity from and to the Big Sky North Substation and over the Interconnection Facilities in an amount equal to such User’s Reserved Capacity. Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, each User separately owns and shall own the electrical energy, capacity, and ancillary services generated by, or associated with, its Project.
5.2 Interconnection Facilities Representatives. On or promptly following a User’s Service Commencement Date, such User shall, by written notice to the other Users and Interconnection Provider, designate an individual (the “Interconnection Facilities Representative”), who will have authority to bind the User in all matters concerning this Agreement, to communicate on a day-to-day basis with each other User and to direct Interconnection Provider regarding construction, operations, and maintenance issues. Each User may change its Interconnection Facilities Representative at any time and from time to time by prior written notice to the other Users and Interconnection Provider and updating such designation in its Service Agreement.
5.3 Liens. Neither the Interconnection Provider nor any User shall, directly or indirectly, create, incur, or permit to exist any Lien on the Interconnection Facilities, including but not limited to Liens for taxes (other than Permitted Liens), judgments, construction work, repair and restoration, or materials furnished, other than Permitted Liens. The Interconnection Provider and each User shall take prompt steps to discharge any Lien filed against any of the Interconnection Facilities, other than a Permitted Lien. If the Interconnection Provider or the User responsible for the imposition of a Lien fails to discharge promptly any such Lien, the other Parties, in addition to any other rights it may have at law or equity for a breach of this Agreement, shall have the right to notify the responsible User in writing and to take any reasonable action to satisfy, defend, settle or otherwise remove the Lien at the responsible Party’s expense.
5.4 Managed Assets.
5.4.1 Legal Title. Legal and equitable title to the Managed Assets, including all associated land and land rights, shall remain with each respective User and is not altered or affected in any way by this Agreement. Each User retains all rights incident to such legal and equitable title in Managed Assets, provided that the exercise of such rights shall not impair the operation or reliability of the Interconnection Facilities. Each User shall be responsible for all costs of constructing and owning the Managed Assets, in accordance with its respective ownership interests in the Managed Assets, as shown in Exhibit C hereto, and Interconnection Provider may, at the request of the Users, administer the collection of monies needed for the management, operation, maintenance, and repair of the Managed Assets.
5.4.2 Functional Control. By this Agreement, each User authorizes the Interconnection Provider to exercise functional control over the operation of Managed Assets as necessary to effectuate transmission service across the Interconnection Facilities. Such control shall be exercised in accordance with Prudent Industry Practices, and shall comply with all applicable reliability guidelines, policies, standards, rules, regulations, orders, or other requirements of NERC, each respective User’s requirements and operating guidelines, and all applicable requirements of federal or state law or regulatory authorities. Interconnection Provider shall permit each User access to the Managed Assets to the extent of such User’s respective percentage ownership therein, if any, as specified in Exhibit C hereto.
5.4.3 Interconnection Provider as Manager. Each User hereby engages the Interconnection Provider as an independent contractor of the Users to serve at the pleasure of the Users and manage, operate, and maintain the Managed Assets as it does the Interconnection Facilities, and to perform other duties pertaining to the Managed Assets, all as set forth in this Agreement. The Users shall reimburse the Interconnection Provider for such operations and maintenance activities in an amount equal to their relative Cost Percentage in such Managed Assets. The Interconnection Provider accepts such engagement and agrees to perform such duties in accordance with the terms and conditions hereof.
5.4.4 Managed Asset Decisions. All actions or decisions by the Interconnection Provider with respect to a Managed Asset that would impose costs on the owners of such asset shall require the Consent of the Users, who may then direct the Interconnection Provider accordingly, and only upon such direction (unless otherwise expressed herein), shall Interconnection Providers have authority to act on behalf of the respective Users with respect to such any matters relating to the Managed Assets.
5.5 Curtailment of Delivery. The Users shall interrupt or reduce deliveries of electrical power over the Interconnection Facilities if requested to do so by the Interconnection Provider in accordance with the following provisions: (i) after reasonable notice to, and agreement by, Users as to the timing and duration of the curtailment, to maintain, repair, replace, remove, investigate, inspect or test any part of the Interconnection Facilities or Managed Assets in accordance with the terms of this Agreement; (ii) if the interruption or reduction is necessary due to an Emergency, or (iii) if the Interconnection Provider is ordered to do so by CAISO, any other Governmental Authority or regulatory authority with jurisdiction over their Interconnection Facilities or Managed Assets, or a User (or its authorized agent) notifies the Interconnection Provider that such curtailment is required by CAISO or another Governmental Authority or regulatory authority with jurisdiction over their Interconnection Facilities or Managed Assets. The Interconnection Provider shall limit the length of any such interruption or curtailment to that time strictly necessary to correct the problem. Any interruption or curtailment made pursuant to clause (i) above shall be made to the extent commercially reasonable during periods that minimize potential loss of revenue of the User(s) being curtailed. Unless directed otherwise by a Project’s transmitting utility or any other Governmental Authority or regulatory authority with jurisdiction over the Interconnection Facilities, the Interconnection Provider shall work with the Users to allocate curtailment orders issued under sub-clauses (ii) and (iii) of the first sentence of this Section 5.5 among Users as follows:
(a) to the extent such curtailment order is specific to a Project or Projects, the curtailment shall be allocated entirely to such Project or Projects in accordance with the curtailment order; or
(b) to the extent such curtailment order is not specific to a Project or Projects, the curtailment shall be allocated among the Projects pro rata based on the ratio of each Project’s Reserved Capacity to the aggregate Reserved Capacity of all Projects;
provided, however, that if an allocation is made by Interconnection Provider pursuant to (b) above, (x) any Project that has not reached its Commercial Operation Date (defined in the applicable power purchase agreement of the respective User) shall be curtailed in its entirety prior to any curtailment of any Projects that have reached their Commercial Operation Date, and (y) the Parties acknowledge that such allocation is subject to the requirements of applicable Laws and will be as close to the formula described above as Interconnection Provider can accomplish, acting commercially reasonably. To the extent any curtailment is caused by any specific Project(s) or a breach by any specific User(s) of its obligations hereunder or by the action or inaction of any individual User or Users, the User or Users who owns such specific Project(s), whose breach of its obligations hereunder or whose action or inaction caused the curtailment shall reimburse any User owner of a Project that has reached its Commercial Operation Date for all Net Revenue Losses arising from such curtailment, it being hereby agreed that payment of the Net Revenue Losses shall be the affected User’s sole and exclusive remedy against such other User with respect to any losses due to such curtailment. The Parties agree that the actual losses arising between and among themselves due to such curtailment would be difficult to compute and that the methodology for determining such losses set forth above is a good faith estimate of the calculations utilized to determine the actual losses that would be suffered.
6. OBLIGATIONS AND CERTAIN RIGHTS OF THE USERS
6.1 Standards of Performance; Action, Omission or Failure to Perform an Obligation That Results in a Material Adverse Effect on Another User or That User’s Project. Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement to the contrary, each User will develop, construct, operate and maintain its Project and perform its obligations under this Agreement in accordance with (a) all applicable Laws, (b) Prudent Industry Practices, (c) the Interconnection Agreement, the CUP and the applicable terms of the Interconnection Premises Agreements, (d) any and all Governmental Approvals, and (e) the applicable power purchase agreement of each respective User. No User will take any action, omit to take any action or fail to perform any obligation under this Agreement, the Interconnection Premises Agreements, the CUP, the Interconnection Agreement, Governmental Approvals, or power purchase agreements, that materially and adversely affects any other User or another User’s Project or gives rise to a Liability affecting any other User, another User’s Project, or the Interconnection Facilities, including any action, omission or failure to perform an obligation that results in damage to, disconnection of, or an outage of another User’s Project.
6.2 Taxes. The Interconnection Provider shall pay all real and personal property Taxes, general or special, levied against its interests in the Interconnection Facilities before delinquency and before any fine, interest or penalty will become due or be imposed for their non-payment, except that the Interconnection Provider may withhold payment of any Tax if Interconnection Provider is contesting the payment of such Tax in good faith by appropriate proceedings and such proceeding does not involve any danger of the sale, forfeiture or loss of any part of such Interconnection Facilities, including the posting of any bond that is required by applicable Law to avoid such sale, forfeiture or loss while the payment of such Tax is being contested and notifies all the Users thereof in writing at least thirty (30) days before such payment is due. All such Taxes and assessments paid by the Interconnection Provider shall be treated as Interconnection Expenses and invoiced to the Users in accordance with Section 4.3.
6.3 Environmental Compliance. Each User shall, with respect to its Project, (including its Project Specific Assets, including the Project Site upon which its Project is installed), be responsible for and shall have exclusive control over all investigations, studies, cleanup, corrective action or response, or remedial action required by (i) any Governmental Authority now or hereafter authorized to regulate environmental or other matters, or (ii) any consent decree or court or administrative order now or hereafter applicable to such User’s use, operation or ownership of its Project (including its Project Specific Assets and Project Site). The Interconnection Provider shall, with respect to the Interconnection Premises and the Interconnection Facilities located on the Interconnection Premises oversee all investigations, studies, cleanup, corrective action or response, or remedial action required by any Governmental Authority now or hereafter authorized to regulate environmental or other matters or by any consent decree or court or administrative order now or hereafter applicable to the Users’ use of the Interconnection Premises or the Interconnection Facilities located on the Interconnection Premises, and subject to Sections 11.1 and 11.2, each User shall be responsible, in proportion to its relative Cost Percentage, for all Liabilities related to such investigations, studies, cleanup, corrective action or response, or remedial action. Interconnection Provider shall keep all Users fully appraised as to the above matters affecting the Interconnection Premises and shall consult with all of them prior to taking any action involving any Governmental Authority or risk of incurring any Liability.
6.4 Interconnection. Each User shall be solely responsible for securing for its own benefit, and for maintaining, such rights as are necessary to interconnect its Project with the transmission and interconnection system controlled by the CAISO and to deliver the electrical energy generated or discharged by its Project, or such portion of the electrical energy generated or discharged by its Project, as is consistent with the terms and conditions of this Agreement. For the avoidance of doubt, each User will separately deliver and meter the electrical energy generated or discharged by its Project and delivered to the Interconnection Facilities.
6.5 Relationship of the Users. The rights, duties, obligations and Liabilities of the Users under this Agreement will be individual and not joint or collective, and no User shall be responsible for the default of any other User under this Agreement. It is not the intention of the Users to create, nor will this Agreement be deemed to create, any partnership, agency, joint venture, trust, or association of profit, or to authorize any User to act as an agent, servant or employee for any other User. Each User will remain solely responsible for the actions of its own employees.
6.6 Regulatory Status. Each User operating a Project represents and warrants that it is an EWG, and such Users each covenant to maintain its status as an EWG for so long as they are a Party to this Agreement. No User will take any action that could adversely impact any other User’s ability to qualify as an EWG.
6.7 No Dedication of Property; No Public Access. Each Party agrees that entering into this Agreement, performing its obligations hereunder, or exercising its rights hereunder, either in whole or part, is not intended to be, and shall in no way be construed as or deemed to be a dedication to public or quasi-public use or purpose of any of the Project Specific Assets of the Party, the Project Specific Assets of another Party, any Interconnection Facilities or Interconnection Premises, or any portion of the foregoing. The Users undertake to cooperate in enforcing such requirement for limiting physical access to the Interconnection Facilities and Interconnection Premises, including permitting Interconnection Provider to establish and enforce procedures and protocol for security, safety, and protection of the Big Sky North Facilities. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the Parties shall comply with requirements set forth in any Governmental Approvals.
6.8 Crossing and Collocation Rights. Each User hereunder shall be permitted to cross and encroach upon the Substation Premises with its Project Specific Assets solely to the extent necessary to develop, construct, operate and maintain its Project, provided that any such crossings, encroachments, or overhang shall be subject to the noninterference and overburdening protections of Section 3.4 above. In particular, any User’s exercise of rights under this Section 6.8 shall only be permitted in accordance with Prudent Industry Practices, the Substation Premises Agreements and the CUP, and shall not interfere with or endanger the construction, operation, or maintenance of the Interconnection Facilities or other facilities already in place on the Interconnection Premises. In the event of a conflict in the location or operation of the Interconnection Facilities and any Project Specific Assets on the Interconnection Premises, the Interconnection Facilities shall take priority over the Project Specific Assets, and any Project Specific Assets existing within the Interconnection Premises shall take priority over any subsequent Project Specific Assets requiring the use of the Interconnection Premises.
6.9 SCE Collocation of Monitoring and Control Facilities with Interconnection Facilities. The Parties acknowledge and agree that SCE may require the use of the Interconnection Premises for the collocation of certain control, metering, and monitoring equipment servicing the Projects, and for the connection of the Interconnection Facilities into the SCE Antelope Substation located in Lancaster, California. Interconnection Provider may in its sole discretion grant SCE that access needed for such activities..
6.10 Cooperation. Upon reasonable request of a Party, each other Party will cooperate in the financing or refinancing of such requesting Party’s Project, including the execution of estoppels, consents for the benefit of the Financing Parties and other similar agreements, as well as third party opinions, as may be reasonably requested by the requesting Party and its Financing Parties; in the making of any filings required by such requesting Party for regulatory compliance or obtaining Governmental Approvals; and in the operation and maintenance of such requesting Party’s Project, all solely at the expense of the requesting Party.
6.11 Users’ Responsibilities to Interconnection Provider. The Users shall do all of the following:
6.11.1 with the exception of information and data the Interconnection Provider is required to record and collect hereunder, provide the Interconnection Provider with all material information, including but not limited to permits, agreements, data and documents, that is reasonably required for Interconnection Provider to perform its obligations under this Agreement;
6.11.2 examine all material documents submitted by Interconnection Provider and render any necessary decisions pertaining thereto promptly;
6.11.3 promptly make material decisions required under this Agreement or any other agreement that the Interconnection Provider may be requested to administer hereunder and respond to all reasonable requests from Interconnection Provider for approval made hereunder; and
6.11.4 except where the same are being disputed in good faith, promptly make all payments and incur all expenditures required in connection with the Interconnection Facilities in accordance with this Agreement.
6.12 Admission of New Users. The Interconnection Provider may not provide access to the Big Sky North Facilities or service across the Interconnection Facilities to any new User under this Agreement (a “New User”) without Consent of the Users; provided that Consent of the Users shall not be required if (a) the New User is developing an energy generation, storage or transmission project that will, in whole or in part, require access to the Big Sky North Facilities or the use of some component of the Interconnection Facilities, (b) the Independent Engineer has confirmed in writing that the Interconnection Provider owns or has rights to a sufficient amount of transmission capacity over the Interconnection Facilities that is necessary to transmit electric energy from the New User’s Project (in addition to all existing Projects), in accordance with Prudent Industry Practices, without any material degradation in firm service to existing Users, (c) the aggregate Reserved Capacity of all Users, and the aggregate Nameplate Capacity of all Projects, after giving effect to the New User and its Project(s), is not more than 670 MW, (d) the New User agrees to be bound by all the terms and conditions contained herein and such other amendments and documentation as may be reasonably requested by the Interconnection Provider, (e) the New User is an Eligible Customer; and (f) Interconnection Provider has received FERC authorization, if applicable. Within one (1) month of a New User’s Service Commencement Date under this Agreement, the Interconnection Provider shall notify the New User and existing Users of the admission of a New User and provide (i) documentation regarding satisfaction of clause (b) above, (ii) an updated Capacity Log, and (iii) an updated Exhibit C.
6.13 Reimbursement for Net Revenue Loss. To the extent any User suffers a Net Revenue Loss as a result of a breach by Interconnection Provider of Section 6.12, the Interconnection Provider shall reimburse the affected User for its Net Revenue Loss within thirty (30) days of notice and supporting documentation of the Net Revenue Loss.
7. INTERCONNECTION PROVIDER REIMBURSEMENT
7.1 Interconnection Provider Reimbursement.
7.1.1 Reimbursement of Expenses. The Interconnection Provider shall be paid or reimbursed for any unscheduled maintenance, repairs to and replacements of the Big Sky North Facilities and for any payments Interconnection Provider makes with respect to the Big Sky Facilities in accordance with Section 4.2. The Interconnection Provider shall have the right to pre-invoice the Users for any materials and components required to be provided hereunder, and not to proceed with the acquisition of such materials and components unless payment has been received by Interconnection Provider for such materials and components, except in cases of Emergency. The reimbursed expenses shall be allocated among, and paid by, all those Users in proportion to their respective Cost Percentage.
7.1.2 Untimely Payment. In the event any User fails to make timely payment of a properly rendered invoice in accordance with this Agreement, then such User failing to pay its respective allocated share of such invoiced amount in accordance with this Agreement shall be jointly and severally responsible for any interest charged by a vendor or contractor as a result of the late payment of such invoice.
8. DUTIES OF THE INTERCONNECTION PROVIDER
8.1 In General. The Interconnection Provider shall cause the Big Sky North Facilities to be constructed, operated, and maintained in accordance with (a) all applicable Laws, (b) Prudent Industry Practices, (c) the terms and conditions of the Interconnection Premises Agreements, the Substation Premises Agreements and the CUP, (d) applicable Governmental Approvals, (e) all applicable requirements of CAISO and SCE, including but not limited to requirements set forth in the Interconnection Agreement, and (f) the terms and provisions of this Agreement.
8.2 Reporting; Notices; Records. The Interconnection Provider shall, from time to time, provide reports to the Users sufficient to keep the Users reasonably apprised as to significant matters concerning the maintenance and repair of the Interconnection Facilities, including such matters related thereto as may have a material impact on the operation, maintenance and repair of each User’s Project. Without limiting the foregoing, Interconnection Provider shall provide to each User an updated Capacity Log and Cost Percentage (a) within thirty (30) days after the end of each calendar year and (b) at least thirty (30) days prior to any User connecting a new Project to the Interconnection Facilities.
8.3 Access; Audit Rights. The Interconnection Provider shall allow the Users and the Users’ authorized Representatives reasonable access to inspect and audit the books and records maintained by the Interconnection Provider with respect to the Interconnection Facilities (at the Users’ sole cost and expense); provided, that the Users shall only have the right to inspect and audit such books and records for any period that is within two (2) calendar years from the date of an applicable payment made hereunder or the final settlement or disposition of any claim made pursuant to this Agreement. If any such inspection or audit discloses an error and that, as a result thereof, any overpayment or any underpayment has occurred hereunder, the amount thereof shall be paid within thirty (30) days after receipt of an invoice (with reasonable supporting detail) with interest (except that any underpayment caused by the actions or inactions of Interconnection Provider will not bear interest) at the Default Rate to the Party to whom it is owed by the other Parties obligated therefor; provided, that a Party shall only be liable for any amounts hereunder that relate to errors discovered and disclosed within the inspection and audit period provided for in this provision.
8.4 Emergencies. In the event of any Emergency involving the Interconnection Facilities, the Interconnection Provider shall take such action as may be reasonable and necessary to prevent, avoid or mitigate injury, loss of life, or damage or destruction of property and shall, as soon as reasonably practicable, report any such Emergency, including the Interconnection Provider’s response thereto, to the Users.
8.5 Cooperation with Lenders and Other Financing Parties. Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, Interconnection Provider shall, during normal business hours and upon reasonable prior notice, cooperate with Users’ Financing Parties and their advisors and consultants and shall make all information, reports, logs and other documents relating to the Interconnection Facilities and Interconnection Premises available to such Financing Parties and their advisors and consultants, and shall make Interconnection Provider’s personnel available for consultation with such Financing Parties and their advisors and consultants, all as reasonably requested and at the respective User’s expense. The Interconnection Provider also agrees that it shall, at any time and from time to time during the term of this Agreement, after receipt of a written request by any of the Users, execute and deliver to such Users and/or any Financing Parties, any consents to collateral assignments or estoppel statements, or facilitate third party opinions, as may reasonably be requested.
8.6 Obligations. The Interconnection Provider shall have no liability for any obligations except those expressly stated in this Agreement, and nothing in this Agreement shall obligate the Interconnection Provider to perform any duties or assume any liabilities under any agreement to which the Interconnection Provider is not directly a party unless such duties are also expressly stated in this Agreement and then only to such extent.
8.7 Inspection by Users. Each User, through its employees, agents, Financing Parties, experts or Representatives, has the right, at all reasonable times, at its own expense, to inspect or cause to be inspected, the Interconnection Facilities and the services of Interconnection Provider hereunder. The Interconnection Provider at all times will retain responsibility for the services that meet the requirements of this Agreement, regardless of whether or not the Users have reviewed or inspected such services, plans, documentation or other acts or items.
8.8 Loss Events. Upon the occurrence of a Loss Event, the Interconnection Provider shall, as soon as reasonably practicable, (a) prepare a written proposal (a “Restoration Proposal”) in consultation with the Users to rebuild, repair, restore or replace the portion of the Big Sky North Facilities affected by such Loss Event, which Restoration Proposal shall contain, in appropriate detail, (i) a budget identifying all categories and approximate amounts reasonably anticipated to be incurred, (ii) a progress and completion schedule and (iii) a written plan, in each case, for the proposed rebuilding, repair, restoration or replacement of the Big Sky North Facilities and (b) perform all services necessary to carry out such plan, including contracting for the services and equipment required; provided, that if insurance proceeds are insufficient to restore the Interconnection Facilities and any User would be required expend more than $1,000,000 in connection with the Restoration Proposal, the restoration shall be subject to the Consent of the Users. The Interconnection Provider, to the extent necessary or prudent, may coordinate preparation of the Restoration Proposal with similar activity undertaken by or on behalf of any of the Users arising out of the Loss Event in respect of Project Specific Assets. Any costs, expenses or other Liabilities associated with the preparation of the Restoration Proposal shall be Interconnection Expenses reimbursed by each User as provided under Agreement. To the extent that consent is required, within 30 days after receipt of a Restoration Proposal from the Interconnection Provider, each applicable User shall notify the Interconnection Provider and each other User in writing of whether it elects to participate in the rebuilding, repair, restoration or replacement of the Big Sky North Facilities. Any costs, expenses or other Liabilities associated with the rebuilding, repair, restoration or replacement of the portion of the Big Sky North Facilities affected by a Loss Event (net of insurance proceeds) shall be Interconnection Expenses reimbursed by each User in proportion to its Cost Percentage. Any User that fails to pay its portion of the Interconnection Expenses within the thirty (30) day period specified above, shall be deemed to have terminated its Service Agreement and status as a User as of the earlier of (i) the date of its election or (ii) the end of such 30 day period.
8.9 Warranties. The Interconnection Provider shall be responsible for enforcing all manufacturer, constructor and other warranties with respect to the Interconnection Facilities and any parts or materials associated therewith. The Interconnection Provider shall have rights to any excess warranty funds. The Interconnection Provider’s out-of-pocket costs and expenses incurred in enforcing said warranties shall be included in the Interconnection Expenses shared by the Users hereunder.
8.10 Disconnection From Interconnection Facilities. Interconnection Provider shall disconnect a User’s Project from the Interconnection Facilities, and each User hereby authorizes the Interconnection Provider to implement such disconnection on behalf of the Users, under any of the following circumstances:
8.10.1 a User is exercising its remedies as permitted under Section 14.2.2;
8.10.2 upon termination or abandonment of a Project by a User or withdrawal from this Agreement by a User; or
8.10.3 if disconnection is necessary for safety in order to perform maintenance to the Interconnection Facilities or in the event of an Emergency affecting a User with an interest in such Interconnection Facility requiring such disconnection.
9. REPRESENTATIONS AND WARRANTIES
9.1 Representations and Warranties. Each Party represents and warrants to each other Party that:
