CO-TENANCY RIGHTS AND OBLIGATIONS [RESERVED].Use of LGIA. The LGIA shall be held and used solely to permit the interconnection of electricity generated by or on behalf of a Phase owned by a Co-Tenant (or by such Co-Tenant’s successors or assigns) at the Antelope Substation. Each Co-Tenant shall have an undivided ownership interest as tenant-in-common in the LGIA, and possess an undivided right to enjoy all of such interest as an Interconnection Customer under the LGIA. The Parties agree that, for the purposes of the LGIA: (i) the entire 650 net MW comprising the Big Sky Solar Expansion Project shall be considered to be a single Large Generating Facility (as defined in the LGIA); (ii) neither the Interconnection Customer nor individual Co-Tenant may have any expectation that the Participating TO will treat any portion of the Big Sky Solar Expansion Project as a stand-alone Generating Facility (as defined in the LGIA) or differently from any other portion of the Generating Facility; (iii) the Co-Tenants shall act as a single entity in undertaking the obligations of Interconnection Customer under the LGIA; (iv) the Participating TO shall treat all Co-Tenants comprising the Interconnection Customer as a single entity under the LGIA and bear no obligation or responsibility to any individual Co-Tenant; and (v) performance of the Interconnection Customer’s obligations under the LGIA shall not be excused by reason of any other Co-Tenant’s failure to agree with respect to any obligation of the Interconnection Customer hereunder or thereunder. Maximum Capacity. No Co-Tenant shall interconnect its respective Phase to the Antelope Substation to the extent such interconnection will result in such Co-Tenant having a Phase with a Net Nameplate Capacity in excess of the Interconnection Capacity allocated to such Phase in the LGIA. To the extent that conditions exist which result in a Co-Tenant generating energy from its respective Phase in excess of its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest of the Interconnection Capacity, then such Co-Tenant shall curtail the operation of its Phase so as not to exceed its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest of the Interconnection Capacity. Curtailment. In the event of any curtailment of interconnection services at the direction of CAISO or Participating TO, such curtailment shall be allocated pro rata among the Co-Tenants according to each Co-Tenant’s Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest; provided, however, that the Manager shall only curtail on a non-pro rata basis if such allocation is necessary to comply with the LGIA or CAISO or Participating TO direction, and, in each case, that such non-pro rata allocation will not result in a default under the LGIA or any power purchase agreement to which a Co-Tenant is a party. LGIA Expenses. Each Co-Tenant hereby confirms its obligation to share in the periodic payment of all expenses incurred under the LGIA in accordance with its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest, except as described below.(a) Construction Costs. Antelope Expansion 2 agrees to fund all Construction Costs.(b) LGIA Operating Expenses. Each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for the payment of its share, if any, of the LGIA Operating Expenses according to such Co-Tenant’s Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest. (c) Payment of LGIA Expenses. Except as described in Section 2.5(a) above, the Manager shall, as authorized agent for each Co-Tenant, administer the collection and payment of the LGIA Operating Expenses and other amounts due from the Interconnection Customer(s) under the LGIA. Each Co-Tenant obligated to pay LGIA Operating Expenses and other amounts under the LGIA shall pay each invoice for LGIA costs promptly upon receipt of written notice thereof from the Manager, but in any event within thirty (30) days of such receipt or such earlier time as required by the LGIA.(d) Notice of Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest. Each Co-Tenant shall notify the other Parties within ten (10) days of its Phase becoming connected and Energized and the Co-Tenant then being allocated a Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest. Liquidated Damages; Credits, Refunds. To the extent that the Manager receives any damages, credits or refunds pursuant to the LGIA, the Manager shall promptly remit such damages, credits or refunds to the Co-Tenants according to each Co-Tenant’s Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest (unless such damages, credits or refunds accrue to a specific Co-Tenant, in which event the Manager shall promptly remit them to such Co-Tenant).Joint and Several Liability. As required by the LGIA, each Co-Tenant shall be jointly and severally liable for (i) any payments due under the LGIA imposed on the Interconnection Customer(s), (ii) the performance of the obligations and duties imposed on the Interconnection Customer(s) by the LGIA, and (iii) the performance of the Manager under the LGIA; provided, however, that each Party shall be severally, and not, jointly liable for all other obligations hereunder. Projected Capacity. To the extent that a Co-Tenant plans that the Net Nameplate Capacity for a Phase will differ from the value identified in the LGIA or Exhibit A to this Agreement, such Co-Tenant shall notify the Manager and the other Co-Tenants in writing, no later than thirty (30) days before such Co-Tenant’s Construction Commencement Date, of the planned Net Nameplate Capacity of its Phase, provided that each Co-Tenant’s Net Nameplate Capacity is subject to Section 2.3 and may not exceed such Co-Tenant’s Maximum Net Nameplate Capacity. Indemnity. (a) Each Co-Tenant (an “Indemnifying Co-Tenant”) shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Co-Tenants (each, an “Indemnified Co-Tenant”) from and against any and all losses (including all lost revenues under applicable power purchase agreements), damages, liabilities, claims, judgments, liens, penalties, costs and expenses, including, without limitation, reasonable attorneys’ and consultants’ fees (collectively, “Claims”), which may be imposed upon or incurred by such Indemnified Co-Tenant or asserted against such Indemnified Co-Tenant in connection with any breach by the Indemnifying Co-Tenant of this Agreement or the LGIA.(b) The Manager shall indemnify, defend, and hold harmless the Co-Tenants from any Claims which may be imposed upon or incurred by such Co-Tenants as a result of fraud, willful misconduct, or gross negligence of the Manager, or in connection with any breach by the Manager of this Agreement or the LGIA. Taxes. Each Co-Tenant shall pay all real and personal property taxes and assessments, general or special, levied against its Phase, except for any taxes or assessments that are LGIA Operating Expenses. All such taxes and assessments shall be paid before delinquency and before any fine, interest or penalty shall become due or be imposed for their non-payment; provided if a Co-Tenant in good faith contests or disputes such taxes or assessments and furnishes to the other Co-Tenants a bond or other acceptable security in an amount sufficient to discharge all such contested taxes or assessments, such Co-Tenant will not be in default under this Section 2.10 for failing to timely pay such contested taxes or assessments. Operation and Management.(a) Each Co-Tenant shall operate and maintain its Phase Controlled Assets acting as a prudent operator and manager and otherwise (a) in accordance with the terms of the LGIA, (b) in accordance with good operating and utility industry practices, in compliance with all applicable Laws, including but not limited to the Federal Power Act, as amended (“FPA”), and all rules, regulations, and orders issued by the FERC pursuant to the FPA, (d) in compliance with the CAISO Tariff, including the rules, protocols, procedures and standards attached thereto, as the same may be amended from time to time and approved by FERC, (e) in compliance with the rules, protocols, procedures and standards of NERC, as applicable, and (t) without causing a material adverse effect on the LGIA.(b) Each Co-Tenant shall comply with its obligations under the LGIA, including with respect to its obligations to fund LGIA Operating Expenses. Each Co-Tenant shall obtain, prior to its respective Phase becoming connected and Energized, and thereafter maintain status under applicable Law as an “exempt wholesale generator” or, if, and for so long as, such Phase meets the criteria of a qualifying small power production facility, as set forth in 18 C.F.R. § 292.204, a “qualifying facility.” BSN shall obtain and maintain status under applicable Law as an “exempt wholesale generator.”(c) Each Co-Tenant shall cooperate with and timely respond to Manager as agent for the Co-Tenants under the LGIA, and shall provide Manager such information required by Manager to comply with its obligations under the LGIA.(d) With respect to jointly held assets, the Co-Tenants may delegate to the Manager some or all of their respective obligations under this Agreement. Events of Default; Default. The following shall constitute “Events of Default”: a Party fails to perform its obligations under this Agreement or the LGIA in any material respect, and such Party fails to cure such default within (i) ten (10) days after receipt of written notice of a payment default, or (ii) twenty (20) days after receipt of written notice of any non-payment default, provided if the nature of the defaulted obligation or obligations other than a payment default is such that more than thirty (30) days are required, in the exercise of commercially reasonable diligence, for cure of such default, then such Co-Tenant shall not be in default under this Section 2.12 if it commences to cure such default within twenty (20) days after receiving notice of the default and thereafter continuously pursues the same to completion with commercially reasonable diligence, such extended period not to exceed sixty (60) days, including the initial cure period. Remedies. Subject to the last sentence of Section 5.8, in addition to all other remedies permitted by Law or under this Agreement (all of which shall be cumulative), following an Event of Default, each non-defaulting Party shall have the right, but not the obligation, to perform the obligations of the defaulting Party, and the defaulting Party shall reimburse the performing Parties for their expenses which they incurred in rendering the performance, plus interest at the Interest Rate. Disconnection. (a) If a Co-Tenant fails to cure any default of it under this Agreement or the LGIA within twenty five (25) days after receiving notice of such default, the Manager may disconnect the breaching Co-Tenant’s Phase from the Antelope Substation (i) after obtaining written approval to do so from the Co-Tenants then not in default, or (ii) without approval from the Co-Tenants then not in default but only to the extent necessary to prevent or cure a “Default” under the LGIA; provided if the nature of the defaulted obligation or obligations is such that more than thirty (30) days are required, in the exercise of commercially reasonable diligence, for cure of such default, then the Manager may not disconnect the defaulting Co-Tenant’s Phase if such Co-Tenant commences to cure such default within twenty five (25) days after receiving notice of the default and thereafter continuously pursues the same to completion with commercially reasonable diligence, such extended period not to exceed eighty five (85) days, including the initial cure period; provided further, that in no event shall any cure period hereunder extend beyond any applicable cure period under the LGIA.(b) To the extent caused by a Co-Tenant’s default hereunder, the Manager may also disconnect such Co-Tenant’s Phase in order to prevent damage to the other Co-Tenants’ Phases, the Interconnection Facilities or the property of the Participating TO or as otherwise needed to prevent or mitigate technical issues affecting the Phases; the Manager shall immediately notify the Co-Tenants of any such disconnection. Equitable Relief. The Parties agree that damages may be an inadequate remedy for a breach by the Manager or any other Party of its respective obligations under this Agreement, and that each Party shall be entitled to seek injunctive and other equitable relief, including specific performance, against any other Party or the Manager to prevent or eliminate such default. Dispute Resolution. (a) Submission. In the event any Party has a dispute, or asserts a claim, that arises out of or in connection with this Agreement or the LGIA, such Party (the “Disputing Party”) shall provide the other Parties with written notice of the dispute or claim (“Notice of Dispute”). Such dispute or claim shall be referred to a designated senior representative of each Party for resolution on an informal basis as promptly as practicable after receipt of the Notice of Dispute by the Parties. In the event the designated representatives are unable to resolve the claim or dispute through unassisted or assisted negotiations within thirty (30) days of the other Parties’ receipt of the Notice of Dispute, such claim or dispute may, upon mutual agreement of the Parties, be submitted to arbitration and resolved in accordance with the arbitration procedures set forth below. In the event the Parties do not agree within such thirty (30) day period to submit such claim or dispute to arbitration, each Party may exercise whatever rights and remedies it may have in equity or at law consistent with the terms of this Agreement.(b) Arbitration Procedures. Any arbitration initiated under this Agreement shall be conducted before a single neutral arbitrator appointed by the Parties. The arbitrator shall be knowledgeable in electric utility matters, including electric transmission and bulk power issues, and shall not have any current or past substantial business or financial relationships with any party to the arbitration (except prior arbitration). The arbitrator shall provide each of the Parties an opportunity to be heard and, except as otherwise provided herein, shall conduct the arbitration in accordance with the rules and procedures for arbitration of complex business disputes for Judicial Arbitration and Mediation Services, Inc. (“Arbitration Rules”) and any applicable FERC regulations; provided, however, in the event of a conflict between the Arbitration Rules and the terms of this Section 2.16, the terms of this Section 2.16 shall prevail.(c) Arbitration Decisions. Unless otherwise agreed by the Parties, the arbitrator shall render a decision within ninety (90) days of appointment and shall notify the Parties in writing of such decision and the reasons therefor. The arbitrator shall be authorized only to interpret and apply the provisions of this Agreement and the LGIA and shall have no power to modify or change any provision of such agreements in any manner. The decision of the arbitrator shall be final and binding upon the Parties, and judgment on the award may be entered in any court having jurisdiction. The decision of the arbitrator may be appealed solely on the grounds that the conduct of the arbitrator, or the decision itself, violated the standards set forth in the Federal Arbitration Act or the Administrative Dispute Resolution Act. The final decision of the arbitrator must also be filed with FERC if it affects jurisdictional rates, terms and conditions of service, Interconnection Facilities, or Network Upgrades.(d) Costs. Each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for its own costs incurred during the arbitration process and for an equal share of the cost of the arbitrator chosen, if applicable. Effect of Force Majeure. If, because of an event of Force Majeure, any Party is unable to carry out its obligations under this Agreement, and if such Party promptly gives the other Parties written notice of such Force Majeure in detail, specifying the nature, extent and expected duration of such Force Majeure, the non-payment obligations and liabilities of the Party giving such notice and the corresponding obligations and liabilities of any other Party shall be temporarily suspended to the extent made necessary by and during the continuance of such Force Majeure; provided, that in no event will the suspension of a Party’s obligations and liabilities hereunder be permitted to cause a “Default” under the LGIA. Any disabling effects of such event of Force Majeure shall be eliminated as soon as and to the extent reasonably practicable by the Party claiming Force Majeure. Notice of Default. Each Co-Tenant and the Manager shall promptly provide written notice to the other Parties upon receiving notice of, or otherwise discovering, any default or potential default under this Agreement or the LGIA or receiving any other notice under the LGIA. Generator Downsizing Process. In the event that the Commercial Operation Date with respect to a Phase is reached and such Phase has a total megawatt capacity amount that is lower than the amount specified in the LGIA by an amount greater than the de minimis threshold of Appendix DD of the CAISO Tariff, the Manager shall submit (on behalf of such Interconnection Customer), or cause such Interconnection Customer to submit, a completed Generator Downsizing Request application and deposit with respect to the uncompleted capacity of such Phase to the CAISO during the last Generator Downsizing Request Window applicable to such Phase. The Co-Tenant for such Phase will be responsible for payment of all deposits and other obligations for study costs, executing agreements required by CAISO in the Generator Downsizing Process, all costs to amend the LGIA and any other costs incurred in connection with the Generator Downsizing Process. MANAGER Appointment of Manager; Manager Services. Each Co-Tenant hereby appoints the Manager to act as its agent and representative for all purposes under the LGIA, and, unless otherwise agreed by the Co-Tenants, the Manager shall have the power to exercise and shall exercise any and all of the rights of the Interconnection Customer(s) under the LGIA and shall coordinate compliance with the LGIA by the Co-Tenants; provided that the Manager may not terminate, amend or Transfer the LGIA or waive any material rights of the Co-Tenants under the LGIA or initiate or settle any dispute resolution under the LGIA, without the prior, unanimous written consent of the Co-Tenants. In addition, each Co-Tenant specifically authorizes the Manager to negotiate and, with the Co-Tenants’ prior written consent, execute on its behalf and on behalf of the Interconnection Customer(s), and agrees to be bound by the terms of, (i) a CAISO meter service agreement, (ii) a CAISO participating generator agreement and (iii) a retail electricity service agreement; provided that, to the extent that the Manager acts as agent for the Co-Tenants under any such agreement, the Manager may not terminate, amend or Transfer any such agreement or waive any material rights of the Co-Tenants under any such agreement or initiate or settle any dispute resolution under any such agreement, without the prior written consent of a Majority of the Co-Tenants. Each Co-Tenant acknowledges and agrees that the Manager’s actions and representations to the Participating TO shall be binding upon the Interconnection Customer and each individual Co-Tenant. Communications. As required by the LGIA, the Manager shall be the single point of contact between the Co-Tenants and the CAISO and the Participating TO, and shall be responsible for all administrative obligations of the Interconnection Customer(s) under the LGIA, including billing, issuing payments, providing notices and communicating with, and receiving instructions from, the CAISO and the Participating TO with respect to the Phases and the LGIA. The Manager shall, promptly upon receipt, provide to each Co-Tenant a copy of any notices or other material communications received by it under the LGIA. All payments, insurance and security to be provided by the Interconnection Customer to the Participating TO pursuant to the LGIA shall be provided only by the Manager on behalf of all Co-Tenants. The Manager shall, from time to time or at the reasonable request of any of Parties or their Financing Parties, provide reports to the Parties and their Financing Parties sufficient to keep the Parties and their Financing Parties reasonably apprised as to significant matters concerning the LGIA, the Construction Costs and the LGIA Operating Expenses. As used herein, “Discriminate” means a failure by the Manager to provide services hereunder in a manner that treats alike each of the Co-Tenants under substantially similar conditions, and for which dissimilar treatment is not otherwise justified as necessary in accordance with prudent operating and utility industry practices. Performance. The Manager shall perform its obligations under this Agreement (a) in accordance with the terms of the LGIA, (b) in accordance with good operating and utility industry practices, (c) in compliance with all applicable Laws, including but not limited to the FPA, and all rules, regulations, and orders issued by the FERC pursuant to the FPA, (d) in compliance with the CAISO Tariff including the rules, protocols, procedures and standards attached thereto, as the same may be amended from time to time and approved by FERC, (e) in compliance with the rules, protocols, procedures and standards of NERC, if applicable, and (f) without causing a material adverse effect on the LGIA. Termination of LGIA. In the event that CAISO and/or SCE seeks to terminate the LGIA and any Co-Tenant objects to such termination, the Co-Tenants and Manager shall cooperate and take such joint actions as may be reasonably necessary or advisable, in each case, to prevent such termination, including, submitting a written objection to CAISO and/or SCE and/or filing a protest or complaint with FERC. No Co-Tenant may Transfer its rights and obligations under this Agreement or the LGIA; provided, however, that each Co-Tenant shall Transfer (such Transfer not requiring the consent of a Party) its rights and obligations under this Agreement and the LGIA, subject to the terms thereof, to a transferee of its respective Phase Controlled Assets (in which case such transferee shall be assigned and assume all of the Transferring Co-Tenant’s rights and obligations under both this Agreement and the LGIA). As may be or become permitted under the LGIA, a Co-Tenant may also Transfer (such Transfer not requiring the consent of a Party) its rights and obligations under this Agreement and the LGIA, subject to the terms thereof, to a transferee of a portion of its respective Phase Controlled Assets (in which case such transferee shall be assigned and assume the Transferring Co-Tenant’s rights and obligations related to that transferred portion of the Phase Controlled Assets under both this Agreement and the LGIA and the Transferring Co-Tenant will retain its rights and obligations related to the retained portion of the Phase Controlled Assets under both this Agreement and the LGIA). The non-transferring Parties may require as a condition of any such Transfer such approvals from FERC or any other entity as may be required by Applicable Law or contract (if any). The Financing Party shall have the right to do any act or thing required of the encumbering Party under this Agreement, and any such act or thing performed by the Financing Party shall be as effective to prevent an applicable default under this Agreement and/or a forfeiture of any of such Party’s applicable rights under this Agreement as if done by the Party itself.(c) Notice to Financing Party. If Manager issues or receives any notices regarding potential or actual defaults as described in Section 2.18 herein, the Manager, on behalf of the Parties, shall promptly deliver a copy of such notice to all Financing Parties of which it has received notice.(d) Consents to Assignment. Each Party hereby agrees that it shall, no later than five (5) business days after a request by a Party (the “Requesting Party”) (or its Financing Party), execute such consents or estoppel certificates as are reasonably requested by the Requesting Party or its Financing Party.
